Raw dev notes -- Getting Ready for Prime Time: Bugs, Bundles, and Installers

Okay, so this past week has been a whirlwind of getting the Synagogue Display System ready for actual deployment. For anyone just tuning in, this project is basically a custom display application for synagogues to show things like upcoming service times, important announcements, and, crucially, memorial (Yahrzeit) information on a screen in their lobby or sanctuary. The goal is to make it super easy for them to manage and display this info without needing a web browser or complex setup.

This period was all about squashing some gnarly bugs and making it a proper, installable application.

First up, March 14th was a big bug-fix day. I finally tracked down this super annoying midnight UTC date bug that was messing with the Yahrzeit calculations. Date/time stuff is always a headache, especially when you're dealing with local vs. UTC and trying to figure out when "today" actually starts for a specific event. Also fixed some jankiness with image drag and scale – users need to be able to resize those memorial images easily. And, of course, memorial ordering was off, which is a critical feature, so that got sorted. Finally, made sure both the general slideshow and the Yahrzeit slideshow were playing nice together.

March 15th was all about making the app more robust. I realized I was bundling the Heebo font directly, which is fine, but I needed to make sure it was always available and that the font-family order was correct so it actually rendered properly. The *big* one though was user data persistence. I had a moment of panic realizing that if I just bundled everything, every time I pushed an update, it would wipe out all their carefully entered memorial data. That would be a disaster! So, I spent time figuring out how to persist user data (specifically the memorial list) outside the application bundle, specifically in `%APPDATA%`. This means updates won't nuke their data, which is a massive relief and a huge win for usability. Also did some docs updates, adding a backup link and outlining the distribution roadmap, and tidied up the TODO list.

March 16th was mostly documentation – added some demo videos, which are crucial for showing people how to use it, and updated the TODO list again with the backup link and distribution roadmap. It's amazing how much time goes into just documenting things properly.

Then, March 17th was a huge milestone: the installer! I finally got around to creating an Inno Setup installer script. This is a game-changer because it means the synagogue staff won't have to manually copy files around or figure out how to launch the app. The best part? I integrated Task Scheduler autostart, so the app will automatically launch when the computer boots up. This is essential for a display system that needs to be "always on" without manual intervention. Also updated the `CLAUDE.md` (my internal code structure doc) to reflect the new installer script.

What was hard or surprising? That midnight UTC date bug was a real head-scratcher. It's always the subtle off-by-one or timezone issues that take the longest. But the biggest learning curve was definitely figuring out the user data persistence outside the app bundle. It's a common pattern for desktop apps, but it was new territory for me in this specific tech stack. Getting the Inno Setup script just right, especially the Task Scheduler part, also took a bit of trial and error. It's not just about copying files; it's about setting up the environment for the app to run reliably.

Honestly, it feels really good to see this project mature from a collection of scripts into a proper, deployable desktop application. It's a huge step towards getting it into the hands of users. There's a real sense of accomplishment in tackling these "boring but essential" infrastructure tasks like data persistence and installers. It makes the whole thing feel much more professional and robust. It's a good reminder that the "glamorous" features are only as good as the foundation they're built on.

Next up: Final testing and initial pilot deployment.
